{{Use American English|date=November 2013}}{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}
[[File:1549 siftwinnow.jpg|thumb|"Sifting and winnowing" commemorative plaque]]

'''Sifting and winnowing''' is a [[metaphor]] for the academic pursuit of truth affiliated with the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]]. It was coined by [[List of Presidents and Chancellors of the University of Wisconsin–Madison|UW President]] [[Charles Kendall Adams]] in an 1894 final report from a committee exonerating economics professor [[Richard T. Ely]] of censurable charges from state education superintendent [[Oliver Elwin Wells]]. The phrase became a local byword for the tenet of [[academic freedom]].

== History ==

[[File:Ely-Richard-T.jpg|thumb|Professor Richard T. Ely, whose work sparked a state challenge to academic freedom]]
In the 1890s, [[University of Wisconsin]] economics professor [[Richard T. Ely]]'s philosophy and radical practice came under fire from state education superintendent [[Oliver Elwin Wells]].{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}} Ely was known to be liberal and pro-union, having published a book on socialism.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}} Wells protested Ely's socialist beliefs, teaching, and public speaking to UW president [[Charles Kendall Adams]] and the Board of Regents, who did not censure Ely.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}} A committee appointed to address the charges produced a report that exonerated Ely upon acceptance by the regents.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}} The report introduced the idea of "sifting and winnowing":{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}}

{{centered pull quote|As Regents of a university with over a hundred instructors supported by nearly two millions of people who hold a vast diversity of views regarding the great questions which at present agitate the human mind, we could not for a moment think of recommending the dismissal or even the criticism of a teacher even if some of his opinions should, in some quarters, be regarded as visionary. Such a course would be equivalent to saying that no professor should teach anything which is not accepted by everybody as true. This would cut our curriculum down to very small proportions. We cannot for a moment believe that knowledge has reached its final goal, or that the present condition of society is perfect. We must therefore welcome from our teachers such discussions as shall suggest the means and prepare the way by which knowledge may be extended, present evils be removed and others prevented. We feel that we would be unworthy of the position we hold if we did not believe in progress in all departments of knowledge. In all lines of academic investigation it is of the utmost importance that the investigator should be absolutely free to follow the indications of truth wherever they may lead. Whatever may be the limitations which trammel inquiry elsewhere we believe the great state University of Wisconsin should ever encourage that continual and fearless [[sifting]] and [[winnowing]] by which alone the truth can be found. |author=1894 Ely trial committee final report|source=via Herfurth's ''Sifting and Winnowing''{{sfn|Herfurth|1949|ps=, ch. 1.}} }}

[[File:Charles Kendall Adams.jpg|thumb|UW–Madison President Adams, who coined the phrase]]

Ely later referred to the report as the "Wisconsin [[Magna Charta]]" for its guarantees of academic freedom in pursuit of truth.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=46}} In ''Decades of Chaos and Revolution'', Stephen J. Nelson contends that UW's sentiment on academic freedom had been set "well before" the 1890s.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}} He added that the 1894 statement "sounds the trumpet of the fundamental principles of the academy: an unending, unlimited belief in the creed of academic freedom and inquiry."{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=45}}

The "sifting and winnowing" construction was coined by Adams, the UW president, who had defended Ely publicly and read his book.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=46}} It was later invoked by UW–Madison Chancellor [[Robben Wright Fleming]] when responding to protestors during his tenure.{{sfn|Nelson|2012|p=44}}

In a later incident, sociology professor [[Edward Alsworth Ross]] was censured upon inviting anarchist [[Emma Goldman]] to address his class.<ref name="UW kb"/> He did not share her beliefs, but supported her free speech.<ref name="UW kb"/> In memorial of the incident, the Class of 1910 created a commemorative "sifting and winnowing" plaque of the phrase in its context, which the regents rejected.<ref name="UW kb"/> After the Class appealed to area newspapers, the regents relented.<ref name="UW kb"/> The plaque was installed on [[Bascom Hall]] in 1915, where it remains.<ref name="UW kb"/> It was rededicated in 1957.<ref name="UW kb"/>

